{{Infobox organization | image = IvyBates College.jpg | caption = Ivy growing on the side of [[Hathorn Hall]], featuring respective classes' Ivy Stones | formation = | type = University and college tradition | footnotes = Founded in 1873 | name = Ivy Day | named_after = The ivy plant, [[Hedera]] | region = [[New England]], [[Northeastern United States]] | founding_location = }}
'''Ivy Day''' is an annual ceremony in which an '''ivy stone''' is placed on either a residential, academic or administrative building or ground to commemorate academic excellence. The ceremony is most known for being practiced among older colleges in the [[Northeastern United States]]. It is most associated with the [[Ivy League]] and a group of small liberal arts college known as the [[Little Ivies]]. Some institutions announce members of [[Phi Beta Kappa Society|Phi Beta Kappa]] and specialized honor designations for students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/events/commencement.php|title=Smith College: Events|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref> Some classes donate to the college, in the form gates, facades, and door outlines,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://innocents.unl.edu/ivy-day-0|title=Ivy Day {{!}} Innocents Society {{!}} University of Nebraska–Lincoln|last=Network|first=University of Nebraska-Lincoln {{!}} Web Developer|website=innocents.unl.edu|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref> by inscribing or creating their own version of symbolic icons of the college's seal or other prominent insignia. The ivy stones are usually decorated with the graduation date and a symbol that represents the college as a whole or the class as a whole. The most common ivy stone is one-by-two feet and is usually made out of workable stone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.library.upenn.edu/exhibits/pennhistory/ivystones/ivystones.ica.html|title=Penn History-ICA Ivy Stone Brochure|website=www.library.upenn.edu|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref>
On occasion students have featured prominent alumni on their class ivy stones or have selected to feature an engraving of a member of their graduating class. Since 1873 at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] and since 1879 at [[Bates College]], students have unveiled class ivy stones at the annual ivy day preceding [[Commencement Day|commencement]].<ref>[http://www.library.upenn.edu/exhibits/pennhistory/ivystones/ivystones.ica.html Penn website] (accessed February 27, 2009)</ref><ref>[http://www.bates.edu/x61823.xml Bates College website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414113219/http://www.bates.edu/x61823.xml |date=2009-04-14 }} (accessed February 27, 2009)</ref> Students may also have a selective procession prior to the official commencement walk to honor each stone being placed on the buildings. On some occasions students plant [[Hedera|ivy]] in front or on the side of their ivy stones.<ref>[http://www.bates.edu/x61823.xml Bates College website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414113219/http://www.bates.edu/x61823.xml |date=2009-04-14 }} (accessed February 27, 2009)</ref> [[Princeton University]] also places class ivy stones on the walls of its buildings, a few days prior to their commencement. Students are known to give speeches at Ivy Day to commemorate their time and work at the college.<ref>[http://www.library.upenn.edu/exhibits/pennhistory/ivystones/ivystones.ica.html UPENN website] (accessed February 27, 2009)</ref> Select medical schools also participate in Ivy Day prior to their [[White coat ceremony|White Coat Ceremony]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tulane.edu/som/student-affairs/graduation/ivy-day.cfm|title=Tulane University - School of Medicine - ivy-day|website=tulane.edu|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref>
